*Method and Architecture for Method and architecture for data transformation, normalization, profiling, cleansing and validation  "Patent Application No. 10/635891 Pub. No. 20040083199."
*Relational Access Manager
**In 1986 McGoveran developed the Relational Access Manager (RAM), middleware software<ref>[http://www.dbdebunk.com/2015/04/david-mcgoveran-interview.html#more Pascal, F. (April 11, 2015). An Interview with David McGoveran. "Database Debunkings".]</ref><ref>[http://www.AlterantiveTech.com/ATpubs_dir.html McGoveran, D., (1988). Relational Access Manager User's Manual. Alternative Technologies Publications Directory.]</ref> that enabled programmers to develop programs in FORTRAN, COBOL, C, C++, and other languages without having to know a query language such as SQL or QUEL. Based on external specifications, RAM mapped a program's internal data structures (e.g., objects, linked lists, trees, etc.) to and from relational database and executed packaged sequences of query language statements by name. It served as an isolation layer between client-side programs and server-side (or local) DBMS software, so that programs could be independent of the peculiarities of a specific DBMS, its query language dialect, and API. By the summer of 1988, the trade secret software had been licensed to Goldman Sachs and Pacific Telesis.  In 1989, Pacific Telesis reverse engineered RAM and disclosed it to Alternative Technologies' competitors, resulting in a trade secret misappropriation lawsuit. The lawsuit was finally won by Alternative Technologies in 1996, though at the cost of bringing RAM further to market.<ref>McGoveran vs Pacific Telesis Group; Superior Court of California, County of San Francisco, Case No. CGC 89 912650</ref>

